ITT We talk about Daft Punk's new album which you can download from this link.

Initial Impressions:  
1.Get lucky is the best track on this album and even that is unspectacular.  
2.Contact is tolerable but it sounds like music from a film score and not something to even bob your head to.  
3.Album is generally boring and the most overrated thing to drop since Eminem dropped Relapse.  
4.Someone please tell me this is a masterpiece because I don't even think you believe yourself.
fact: if I hear you play Get Lucky at EDC, I will leave.
Fact:  If you hear me play Get Lucky it is not me and you should shoot the imposer on sight.  I play bass house and dark shit not some rehashed nu-disco that is like nails on a chalk board.

this was original in the sense that daft punk tries desperately to resuscitate a genre that is generally not doing TOO bad (disco / nu-disco). This entire album just sounds dead. like lifeless. i don't hate it, its just entirely boring to me. Their old shit had some life and energy to it, its not present here.
Haters gonna hate
You guys are all snobs
http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HzSUo8iPp4M

I agree. It is boring. Really pretty disappointing. That being said I rarely like Daft Punk albums when I first listen to them. It usually takes a few times through, but I didn't hear much that would sway me towards suddenly loving this album. It is just too mellow and lacks the fun their earlier albums were famous for.

Best description of the album so far ^^^^

Not necessarily bad, just not as much fun, and definitely not anything i'd consider to live up to the hype... that being said Giorgio by Moroder is probably my favorite track, especially after the 5:40 mark.

Great quote by Time Out Chicago: "Wavefront is our favorite of Chicago's EDM festivals. For one, it's on sand. Nobody will confuse Montrose Beach for Ibiza, but the popularity of this music was built on the playas of Europe. Two, this lineup is simply better. Electric Daisy and Spring Awakening lean heavy on trance, dubstep and twentysomething mainstreamers. Here, you get a more diverse spread of veterans, outliers and subtler architects of electronic music. Diplo and Justice are the monsters at the top, but the bill runs deep, from bass heads Rusko and Scuba to experimentalist like Damian Lazarus and Nicholas Jaar. In between you've got Crookers, Maya Jane Coles and so many more. The second, er, wave of acts announced includes more titans: Fatboy Slim, James Murphy, Jacques Lu Cont and Holy Ghost! Holy crap! Oh, and there's an entire stage devoted to Chicago house. Did we say this is our favorite EDM festival? Scratch that. This is the best fest in Chicago in 2013."
This is hard not to love...

From The Warehouse to Wavefront, the Chicago-born producers of Wavefront are proud to announce HOUSE COMES HOME: Chicago Heritage of House Stage. The new Chicago Heritage of House Stage will feature the forefathers of house music: Frankie Knuckles, Derrick Carter, Mark Farina, Gene Farris, Jamie Principle, Ralphi Rosario (Original Hot Mix 5 member), Teri Bristol & Psycho Bitch (Crobar) and Mike Serafini (Gramaphone Records).

"I am truly excited to be a part of the Wavefront Music Festival,” says Chicago house music originator Frankie Knuckles. “From the beginning of this whole 'House Music' movement at our little club [The Warehouse] on S. Jefferson St. back in 1977, I couldn't imagine that that little old good time would turn into such a global phenomenon. For better than 25 years I've circled the globe and everywhere I go I leave a little piece of Chicago behind (musically). And now, not only does the world recognize Chicago as a viable entity when it comes to 'House Music' but the City of Chicago fully embraces, supports and recognizes the movement I'm so proud to be a part of. Welcome to The Wavefront Music Festival!”
